    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Civil rights violations, explained</h2>
    <p style="font-size:16px;color:#39414B;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:20px">When a government official — including correctional staff — violates your constitutional rights while acting in their official capacity, that's generally the basis for a civil rights claim under 42 U.S.C. § 1983. These aren't ordinary lawsuits about a bad outcome; they're claims that the Constitution itself was violated. Common examples in custody include excessive force, unconstitutional conditions of confinement, and denial of adequate medical care.</p>

    <h2>Deliberate indifference: a specific, demanding legal standard</h2>
    <p style="font-size:16px;color:#39414B;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:16px">Most medical-neglect claims against correctional staff are analyzed under a standard called <strong>deliberate indifference</strong> — the standard courts use to decide whether inadequate medical care in custody rises to the level of a constitutional violation under the Eighth Amendment. To succeed, a claim generally has to show two things:</p>
    <ul style="font-size:16px;color:#39414B;line-height:1.9;margin-left:24px;margin-bottom:16px">
      <li>An <strong>objectively serious</strong> medical need or risk of harm, and</li>
      <li>That the official <strong>actually knew</strong> about that risk and <strong>disregarded</strong> it anyway</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="font-size:16px;color:#39414B;line-height:1.8">That second element is the hard part. It's a subjective standard — the official has to have actually known and consciously chosen to ignore the risk. Simple carelessness, a missed diagnosis, or an honest medical judgment call that turned out wrong generally isn't enough on its own to meet this standard, even if the outcome was serious.</p>

    <h2>Medical malpractice: a different claim, a different standard</h2>
    <p style="font-size:16px;color:#39414B;line-height:1.8;margin-bottom:16px">Medical malpractice is a separate legal concept from deliberate indifference, and the two get confused constantly. Malpractice is typically a state-law negligence claim: a healthcare provider failed to meet the accepted standard of care, and that failure caused injury. Unlike deliberate indifference, malpractice generally doesn't require showing the provider knew about a risk and ignored it — ordinary negligence can be enough.</p>
    <p style="font-size:16px;color:#39414B;line-height:1.8">In practice, this means two different legal questions can apply to the exact same set of facts: <em>was this bad enough to be malpractice?</em> and, separately, <em>was this bad enough to be a constitutional violation?</em> A case can be one, both, or neither — and figuring out which is exactly the kind of analysis that needs to happen before anything gets filed.</p>

